Hi Thilo

>> There is os commands for that or just generic var=var2 etc. The idcmp
>> message is a pointer to a idcmp structure which contains amongst other
>> things a timestamp. Find a way to get that pointer, it`s easy using the
>> os though: *idcmpmsg=GT_GetImsg(*window\UserPort)

> The Event or WaitEvent command seems to reply the IDCMPmessage already,
> so you are not alowed to read the values outof the structure since it is
> no longer valid after replying.
> 
> Correct me if I am wrong.

You have it correct. However, you can manually peek at the values before
you use Event or WaitEvent (well, Event makes more sense).

Something like this might work IIRC:

*win.Window=Peek.l(Addr Window(0))
Wait_(1 LSL *win\UserPort\mp_SigBit) ; If you want to do a "WaitEvent"
*imsg.IntuiMessage = *win\UserPort\mp_MsgList\lh_Head
; Thats the first message in the queue, which will be the next
; one processed

If *imsg\ExecMessage\mn_Node\ln_Succ<>0
   ; Need to check if there is actually a message there
   sec.l=*imsg\Seconds
   mic.l=*imsg\Micros
EndIf

ev.l=Event
If ev
  ; Normal processing here
EndIf

Of course, this becomes more complicated if you have more than 1 window
open since all messages will be in the same queue and you will need to
make sure you are checking clicks for the correct window.
(*imsg\IDCMPWindow has a pointer to the window which the event came from).

I'd say it would be a lot less hassle to not do this kinda crap though ;)

